of pork sausages.

114
00:06:12,052 --> 00:06:13,144
(AUDIENCE LAUGHING)

115
00:06:13,219 --> 00:06:17,883
The Queensland police are
looking for men
in a long, thin getaway car.

116
00:06:20,927 --> 00:06:22,622
Now, my first guest tonight...

117
00:06:22,696 --> 00:06:23,856
Well, we in the Nixon camp

118
00:06:23,930 --> 00:06:25,397
really didn't know that much
about David Frost,

119
00:06:25,465 --> 00:06:28,457
other than he was
a British talk show host

120
00:06:28,535 --> 00:06:30,298
with something of
a playboy reputation.

121
00:06:30,370 --> 00:06:34,101
He'd had a talk show
here in the US that
had won some awards

122
00:06:34,174 --> 00:06:39,271
but hadn't syndicated well
and had been dropped
by the network.

123
00:06:39,345 --> 00:06:40,835
He ended up taking
it down to Australia,

124
00:06:40,914 --> 00:06:44,645
which is, I believe,
where he was when
the President resigned.

125
00:06:44,918 --> 00:06:47,409
FROST: Next week's guest
will be Evonne Goolagong.

126
00:06:47,487 --> 00:06:49,387
We'll see you then.
God bless.

127
00:06:52,192 --> 00:06:53,887
Great show, David.
Thanks, Noah.

128
00:06:53,960 --> 00:06:55,154
NOAH: Come and look at this.

129
00:06:55,228 --> 00:06:56,354
Nixon leaving
the White House.

130
00:06:56,429 --> 00:06:59,159
<i>NEWS REPORTER. A dark day</i>
<i>for Richard Nixon,</i>
<i>who has drawn crowds</i>

131
00:06:59,232 --> 00:07:00,597
<i>to the vast Ellipse south</i>
<i>of the White House before.</i>

132
00:07:00,667 --> 00:07:02,191
What, this is live?
Yeah.

133
00:07:02,268 --> 00:07:04,930
<i>NEWS REPORTER.</i>
<i>But those were triumphs.</i>
<i>This is not.</i>

134
00:07:05,004 --> 00:07:07,495
What time is it
in Washington?

135
00:07:07,574 --> 00:07:09,007
9:00 a.m.

136
00:07:09,075 --> 00:07:10,201
Why didn't he wait?

137
00:07:10,276 --> 00:07:11,743
It's 6:00 in the morning
on the West Coast.

138
00:07:11,811 --> 00:07:13,904
Half his audience
is still asleep.

139
00:07:15,448 --> 00:07:18,281
All right,
you blokes, let's get
the set broken down.

140
00:07:18,351 --> 00:07:22,412
<i>NEWS REPORTER. ...are</i>
<i>witnesses to the saddest day</i>
<i>in the life of Richard Nixon,</i>

141
00:07:22,489 --> 00:07:26,425
<i>his last moments</i>
<i>as President</i>
<i>of the United States,</i>

142
00:07:26,493 --> 00:07:30,122
<i>a moment unlike</i>
<i>any other in the history</i>
<i>of this country.</i>

143
00:07:47,113 --> 00:07:48,978
<i>Richard Nixon, who goes now</i>

144
00:07:49,048 --> 00:07:51,312
<i>from the power</i>
<i>of the presidency</i>

145
00:07:51,384 --> 00:07:53,614
<i>to a form of exile</i>
<i>in California.</i>

146
00:07:53,686 --> 00:07:56,484
Find out the numbers
for this, will you?
Worldwide.

147
00:08:09,969 --> 00:08:11,869
<i>BRENNAN. I remember his face.</i>

148
00:08:13,373 --> 00:08:15,705
<i>Staring out the window.</i>

149
00:08:15,775 --> 00:08:20,439
<i>Down below him,</i>
<i>a liberal America</i>
<i>cheered, gloated.</i>

150
00:08:22,148 --> 00:08:24,673
Hippies, draft dodgers,
dilettantes,

151
00:08:24,751 --> 00:08:28,118
the same people
who'd spit on me when
I got back from Vietnam.

152
00:08:29,289 --> 00:08:33,316
They'd gotten rid
of Richard Nixon,
their bogeyman.

153
00:08:46,005 --> 00:08:49,031
So what's so important
that it couldn't wait,
that it had to be today?

154
00:08:49,108 --> 00:08:53,545
I've had an idea, John,
rather a bold idea
for an interview.

155
00:08:53,613 --> 00:08:55,080
Fish and chips, please.

156
00:08:55,148 --> 00:08:56,547
And in a moment...

157
00:08:56,616 --> 00:08:57,981
Well, it's too late now.
It's done.

158
00:08:58,051 --> 00:08:59,382
I've called his people...

159
00:08:59,452 --> 00:09:00,612
You?

160
00:09:00,687 --> 00:09:03,053
Beans, peas and lamb, please.

161
00:09:03,122 --> 00:09:04,589
And made an offer.

162
00:09:04,657 --> 00:09:09,117
Now, if the subject
were to say yes,

163
00:09:11,030 --> 00:09:16,525
well, he's rather
a big fish that swims
in not-untricky waters.

164
00:09:17,036 --> 00:09:20,802
So it goes without saying
that I'd want a dear friend

165
00:09:20,874 --> 00:09:23,707
and the finest producer
I know by my side.

166
00:09:28,848 --> 00:09:30,042
So who is it?

167
00:09:31,451 --> 00:09:33,248
Richard Nixon.

168
00:09:33,353 --> 00:09:35,981
(LAUGHS) Richard Nixon?

169
00:09:36,055 --> 00:09:38,455
Well, come on,
don't look like that.

170
00:09:38,524 --> 00:09:40,185
Well, how would you
expect me to look?

171
00:09:40,260 --> 00:09:43,525
I spent yesterday
evening watching you
interview the Bee Gees.

172
00:09:43,596 --> 00:09:45,461
Weren't they terrific?

173
00:09:45,531 --> 00:09:49,524
Come on, John,
we've done political
interviews before.

174
00:09:50,803 --> 00:09:53,294
So, okay, so what
kind of interview?

175
00:09:53,373 --> 00:09:58,606
A full, extensive
look-back over his life,
his presidency.

176
00:09:58,678 --> 00:10:00,236
And?

177
00:10:00,313 --> 00:10:01,746
And what?
Come on, David.

178
00:10:01,814 --> 00:10:03,281
Surely the only thing
that would interest anyone

179
00:10:03,349 --> 00:10:05,681
about Richard Nixon
would be a confession.

180
00:10:05,752 --> 00:10:07,515
A full,
no-holds-barred
confession.

181
00:10:07,587 --> 00:10:09,817
Well, we'll get that, too.

182
00:10:09,889 --> 00:10:10,878
From Richard Nixon?

183
00:10:10,957 --> 00:10:12,288
Come on, John.

184
00:10:12,358 --> 00:10:14,656
Just think of the
numbers it would get.

185
00:10:15,395 --> 00:10:17,056
Do you know how
many people watched

186
00:10:17,130 --> 00:10:18,757
his farewell speech
in the White House?

187
00:10:18,831 --> 00:10:20,856
Four hundred million.

188
00:10:22,235 --> 00:10:24,226
But in the end,
David heard nothing.

189
00:10:24,304 --> 00:10:25,965
And soon after
arriving in California,

190
00:10:26,039 --> 00:10:29,634
Nixon was rushed
to hospital with an acute
attack of phlebitis.

191
00:10:43,089 --> 00:10:45,523
<i>I think it was</i>
<i>around this time</i>
<i>that Gerald Ford,</i>

192
00:10:45,591 --> 00:10:46,615
who was the new President,

193
00:10:46,693 --> 00:10:48,752
and who was desperate
to move the agenda
on from Watergate,

194
00:10:48,828 --> 00:10:51,922
gave Nixon a full,
free and absolute pardon.

195
00:10:51,998 --> 00:10:54,728
<i>Now therefore, I,</i>
<i>Gerald R. Ford,</i>

196
00:10:54,801 --> 00:10:57,463
<i>President of</i>
<i>the United States,</i>

197
00:10:57,537 --> 00:11:01,473
<i>have granted,</i>
<i>and by these presents</i>
<i>do grant,</i>

198
00:11:01,541 --> 00:11:04,066
<i>a full,</i>
<i>free and absolute pardon</i>

199
00:11:04,143 --> 00:11:09,342
<i>unto Richard Nixon</i>
<i>for all offenses</i>
<i>against the United States.</i>

200
00:11:09,415 --> 00:11:11,815
It meant that the man
who had committed
the greatest felony

201
00:11:11,884 --> 00:11:14,546
in American political history
would never stand trial.

202
00:11:14,620 --> 00:11:17,020
It was like he slipped
out the back door.

203
00:11:18,257 --> 00:11:20,020
<i>A public opinion</i>
<i>poll indicates</i>

204
00:11:20,093 --> 00:11:23,460
<i>a two-to-one disapproval</i>
<i>of the pardoning</i>
<i>of Richard Nixon.</i>

205
00:11:23,529 --> 00:11:26,726
<i>CHANCELLOR. One telegram</i>
<i>from Virginia said,</i>
<i>''Roosevelt had his New Deal,</i>

206
00:11:26,799 --> 00:11:30,394
<i>''Truman had his Fair Deal,</i>
<i>now Ford has</i>
<i>his crooked deal. ''</i>

207
00:11:30,470 --> 00:11:32,461
<i>There was no deal, period.</i>

208
00:11:32,538 --> 00:11:34,904
<i>I don't think the truth</i>
<i>will ever come out.</i>

209
00:11:34,974 --> 00:11:36,635
<i>The American people</i>
<i>need to know the truth,</i>

210
00:11:36,709 --> 00:11:39,940
<i>and I don't think</i>
<i>it will ever now</i>
<i>be fully known.</i>

211
00:12:03,069 --> 00:12:05,902
GANNON: So how do we
want to address
the college protests?

212
00:12:05,972 --> 00:12:07,166
Well, do we want
to lift some quotes

213
00:12:07,240 --> 00:12:10,368
from the "stand up
and be counted" speech
in 1970?

214
00:12:10,443 --> 00:12:12,070
Sir?
GANNON: You know, maybe
we're just better off

215
00:12:12,145 --> 00:12:13,669
using the whole
Lincoln Memorial memo.

216
00:12:13,746 --> 00:12:15,213
SAWYER: Just include
the whole thing.

217
00:12:15,281 --> 00:12:17,749
Mr. President,
Swifty Lazar is here.

218
00:12:17,817 --> 00:12:20,081
Okay. No, no, stick around.

219
00:12:20,153 --> 00:12:22,348
You're gonna get
a kick out of this.

220
00:12:22,422 --> 00:12:25,653
This is my literary agent
from Hollywood.

221
00:12:25,725 --> 00:12:27,920
Hygiene obsessive.

222
00:12:30,830 --> 00:12:33,390
Mr. President,
good to see you.

223
00:12:33,466 --> 00:12:35,093
Nice to see you.

224
00:12:35,168 --> 00:12:37,762
These are folks
helping me with my book.

225
00:12:37,837 --> 00:12:40,738
Diane Sawyer,
Frank Gannon,
Irving Lazar.

226
00:12:40,807 --> 00:12:42,365
Nice to meet you.
Miss Sawyer.

227
00:12:42,442 --> 00:12:44,171
Pleasure.
Mr. Gannon.

228
00:12:48,081 --> 00:12:50,106
Okay, that's it.
I'll see you after lunch.

229
00:12:50,183 --> 00:12:52,174
SWIFTY: So how
you feeling, sir?

230
00:12:52,585 --> 00:12:57,147
I'm better, thank you.
Though not yet
well enough to golf,

231
00:12:57,990 --> 00:13:00,857
thank God.
I despise that game.

232
00:13:01,861 --> 00:13:04,386
Imagine, six weeks
out of office

233
00:13:04,464 --> 00:13:06,989
as President
of the United States,

234
00:13:07,066 --> 00:13:09,933
and they'd have me putting
in my hospital room.

235
00:13:10,002 --> 00:13:11,993
Never retire, Mr. Lazar.

236
00:13:12,438 --> 00:13:17,375
To me, the unhappiest
people of the world
are retired.

237
00:13:17,443 --> 00:13:19,240
No purpose.

238
00:13:19,312 --> 00:13:22,076
What makes life mean
something is purpose.

239
00:13:22,148 --> 00:13:25,049
A goal. A battle. A struggle.

240
00:13:25,118 --> 00:13:27,348
Well, even if
you don't win it.

241
00:13:27,854 --> 00:13:30,345
When my doctor
declared me unfit

242
00:13:30,423 --> 00:13:32,254
to give testimony
in the Watergate trial,

243
00:13:32,325 --> 00:13:34,555
everybody thought
I'd be relieved.

244
00:13:34,627 --> 00:13:36,219
Well, they were wrong.

245
00:13:36,295 --> 00:13:37,819
That was the lowest I got.

246
00:13:37,897 --> 00:13:42,334
Well, if it's a challenge
you want, here's one
you might enjoy.

247
00:13:42,401 --> 00:13:46,337
How to spend $2 million,
2.3 to be precise.

248
00:13:46,405 --> 00:13:48,202
It's what I got
for your memoirs.

249
00:13:48,274 --> 00:13:49,741
Well, thank you.

250
00:13:49,809 --> 00:13:51,071
Eh...

251
00:13:51,144 --> 00:13:52,907
It might be a little short
of what I wanted,

252
00:13:52,979 --> 00:13:56,540
but let me assure you,
it's a whole lot more
than they wanted.

253
00:13:56,616 --> 00:13:58,641
That book is important to me.

254
00:13:58,718 --> 00:14:02,415
It's probably the only
chance I'm gonna get
to put the record straight

255
00:14:02,488 --> 00:14:05,855
and remind people
the Nixon years
weren't all bad.

256
00:14:07,326 --> 00:14:11,228
You know, if you're trying
to put the record straight,

257
00:14:11,297 --> 00:14:12,764
I'd at least talk to him.

258
00:14:12,832 --> 00:14:13,958
NIXON: Who?

259
00:14:14,400 --> 00:14:17,733
David Frost.
English talk show guy.

260
00:14:18,471 --> 00:14:21,372
Why would I want to
talk to David Frost?

261
00:14:21,440 --> 00:14:24,238
Well, a while back,
he wrote asking
for an interview.

262
00:14:24,310 --> 00:14:25,641
No.

263
00:14:25,711 --> 00:14:27,042
Well, we didn't
get back to him.

264
00:14:27,113 --> 00:14:29,445
Frankly, we didn't
find him appropriate.

265
00:14:29,515 --> 00:14:32,279
Well, I thought
that we were
doing one with CBS.

266
00:14:32,351 --> 00:14:34,319
We are. I just figured
doing it with Frost

267
00:14:34,387 --> 00:14:36,514
would be a whole lot
easier than doing it
with Mike Wallace.

268
00:14:36,589 --> 00:14:40,923
It would, but it would
have a lot less,
you know, credibility.

269
00:14:40,993 --> 00:14:44,520
True, true. Could
probably get more money.

270
00:14:47,333 --> 00:14:49,096
Really?
Look.

271
00:14:49,168 --> 00:14:52,569
We'll always have
350 on the table
from CBS.

272
00:14:52,638 --> 00:14:56,369
But if I could get
Frost to pay more
and secure better terms,

273
00:14:56,876 --> 00:14:58,969
it might be a shame to pass.

274
00:14:59,545 --> 00:15:02,742
It'd be interesting to know
where he is right now.

275
00:15:03,182 --> 00:15:05,776
We tied him to
railway tracks,
and he escaped.

276
00:15:06,319 --> 00:15:09,117
We buried him alive,
and he walked free.

277
00:15:09,188 --> 00:15:13,591
Today we're lowering
escape artist Derek Harrison
into the water

278
00:15:13,659 --> 00:15:17,993
to see if he can
miraculously
cheat death once more.

279
00:15:18,064 --> 00:15:20,498
Good evening,
and welcome to
<i>Great Escapes.</i>

280
00:15:20,566 --> 00:15:22,500
My name is David Frost.

281
00:15:24,537 --> 00:15:26,129
DIRECTOR:
Okay, that is a cut.

282
00:15:26,205 --> 00:15:27,297
Thank you.

283
00:15:27,373 --> 00:15:30,672
In any deal, you need to
know your opponent's
breaking point.

284
00:15:32,078 --> 00:15:33,773
To assess that,
you might call them

285
00:15:33,846 --> 00:15:36,076
late at night
or at the weekend.

286
00:15:36,716 --> 00:15:39,549
If they take the call,
you know they're desperate.

287
00:15:39,619 --> 00:15:43,055
And from that moment on,
you know you have
the upper hand.

288
00:15:43,589 --> 00:15:45,489
(PHONE RINGING)

289
00:15:54,133 --> 00:15:55,293
Hello?

290
00:15:55,368 --> 00:15:57,063
<i>Mr. Frost? Irving Lazar.</i>

291
00:15:58,437 --> 00:15:59,927
Who?

292
00:16:00,006 --> 00:16:03,169
Swifty Lazar.
I represent
President Nixon.

293
00:16:03,242 --> 00:16:04,504
What time is it?

294
00:16:04,577 --> 00:16:05,566
<i>Bad time?</i>

295
00:16:05,645 --> 00:16:08,443
(STUTTERING) No! Not at all.

296
00:16:11,517 --> 00:16:15,351
I'm calling with regard
to your request
for an interview

297
00:16:15,421 --> 00:16:18,413
and to say,
having considered it,

298
00:16:18,491 --> 00:16:22,484
my client is not
necessarily opposed
to the idea.

299
00:16:22,561 --> 00:16:26,292
Really?
Well, that's
terrific news!

300
00:16:26,365 --> 00:16:28,094
For God's sake.

301
00:16:28,167 --> 00:16:30,226
<i>SWIFTY. I got $500,000.</i>

302
00:16:30,303 --> 00:16:31,702
Is that good?

303
00:16:31,771 --> 00:16:36,401
Mr. President,
it's a half a million dollars
for a news interview.

304
00:16:36,475 --> 00:16:37,737
It's unprecedented.

305
00:16:37,810 --> 00:16:40,005
Yeah? Well, what's the catch?

306
00:16:40,079 --> 00:16:43,242
<i>With Frost? None.</i>
<i>It'll be a big wet kiss.</i>

307
00:16:43,816 --> 00:16:46,444
This guy'll be so grateful
to be getting it at all,

308
00:16:46,519 --> 00:16:48,214
he'll pitch
puffballs all night

309
00:16:48,287 --> 00:16:51,120
and pay a half
a million dollars
for the privilege.

310
00:16:54,493 --> 00:16:56,859
Well, you think
you could get 550?

311
00:16:58,164 --> 00:16:59,495
I got 6.

312
00:17:01,200 --> 00:17:03,065
BIRT: David, how could
you have done that?
What?

313
00:17:03,135 --> 00:17:05,069
$600,000. That's a fortune.

314
00:17:05,137 --> 00:17:06,126
200 on signature?

315
00:17:06,205 --> 00:17:07,672
Don't worry about the money.

316
00:17:07,740 --> 00:17:10,106
My God.
Most Americans think
he belongs in jail.

317
00:17:10,176 --> 00:17:11,871
You're making him
a rich man.

318
00:17:11,944 --> 00:17:13,878
Plus, by outbidding them,
you've already made enemies

319
00:17:13,946 --> 00:17:15,436
of the networks.
They're just jealous.

320
00:17:15,514 --> 00:17:18,039
They're already sounding off
about checkbook journalism.

321
00:17:18,117 --> 00:17:19,550
And if the networks
are against you,

322
00:17:19,618 --> 00:17:21,017
syndication's always
going to be a struggle.

323
00:17:21,087 --> 00:17:22,645
No syndication,
no advance sales.

324
00:17:22,722 --> 00:17:24,246
No advance sales,
no commercials.

325
00:17:24,323 --> 00:17:25,756
No commercials, no revenue.

326
00:17:25,825 --> 00:17:29,488
And here's the bigger
question, why do it?
You don't need it.

327
00:17:29,562 --> 00:17:30,688
Your career's
in great shape.

328
00:17:30,763 --> 00:17:32,924
This will just spread you
across three continents,

329
00:17:32,998 --> 00:17:34,590
jeopardize the other shows.

330
00:17:34,667 --> 00:17:36,066
Isn't it true that
Channel Nine in Australia

331
00:17:36,135 --> 00:17:37,830
want you to do
another season
of your talk show for them?

332
00:17:37,903 --> 00:17:38,961
Yes.
And London, too?

333
00:17:39,038 --> 00:17:41,165
Yes, but that would be
London and Australia.

334
00:17:41,240 --> 00:17:43,003
This would be...
What?

335
00:17:43,609 --> 00:17:45,099
You wouldn't
understand, John.

336
00:17:45,177 --> 00:17:48,010
You were never
part of the show
in New York,

337
00:17:48,647 --> 00:17:50,444
but it's indescribable.

338
00:17:50,516 --> 00:17:55,579
Success in America
is unlike success
anywhere else.

339
00:17:57,022 --> 00:17:59,047
And the emptiness
when it's gone.

340
00:18:00,459 --> 00:18:05,897
And the sickening
thought that it may
never come back.

341
00:18:06,832 --> 00:18:09,198
You know, there's
a restaurant in New York
called Sardi's.

342
00:18:09,268 --> 00:18:11,031
Ordinary mortals
can't get a table.

343
00:18:11,103 --> 00:18:12,798
John, the place
was my canteen!

344
00:18:12,872 --> 00:18:13,964
You know, I'd be happier

345
00:18:14,039 --> 00:18:15,267
if I heard
some kind of vision

346
00:18:15,341 --> 00:18:16,501
that you had
for this interview.

347
00:18:16,575 --> 00:18:17,735
MAN: Excuse me, Mr. Frost.

348
00:18:17,810 --> 00:18:18,936
I'd heard you were
going to be here.

349
00:18:19,011 --> 00:18:20,945
Would you mind?
Of course.

350
00:18:21,013 --> 00:18:22,503
But I don't.
I just hear
a man doing it

351
00:18:22,581 --> 00:18:23,843
because it would
create headlines

352
00:18:23,916 --> 00:18:26,009
or give him a place
at the top table.

353
00:18:26,085 --> 00:18:27,450
And that is what
makes me nervous.

354
00:18:27,520 --> 00:18:30,250
And you do nervous
so beautifully, John.

355
00:18:30,322 --> 00:18:33,621
"Hello, good evening
and welcome."

356
00:18:34,093 --> 00:18:35,617
(FROST LAUGHS)

357
00:18:36,829 --> 00:18:38,763
I don't actually say that.

358
00:18:38,831 --> 00:18:40,389
Hello, Mr. Frost.

359
00:18:46,972 --> 00:18:48,200
Champagne?

360
00:18:48,274 --> 00:18:49,969
CAROLINE: No, thank you.

361
00:18:50,976 --> 00:18:53,035
FLIGHT ATTENDANT:
Another glass, sir?

362
00:19:10,563 --> 00:19:12,724
You don't like champagne?

363
00:19:14,200 --> 00:19:15,758
Not on airplanes.

364
00:19:15,835 --> 00:19:18,133
Yes, it dehydrates
one terribly.

365
00:19:18,971 --> 00:19:21,633
The trick is to have
a glass of water
on the go, too.

366
00:19:21,707 --> 00:19:24,232
Like the Viennese
serve coffee.

367
00:19:24,310 --> 00:19:26,574
Well, I've never
been to Vienna.

368
00:19:26,645 --> 00:19:29,113
Oh. Well, you'd like it.

369
00:19:29,181 --> 00:19:32,207
It's like Paris
without the French.

370
00:19:35,221 --> 00:19:36,779
What's your name?

371
00:19:36,856 --> 00:19:38,050
Caroline.

372
00:19:38,123 --> 00:19:39,147
David.

373
00:19:39,225 --> 00:19:41,921
Yes, I know. David Frost.

374
00:19:42,928 --> 00:19:45,726
"Hello and good evening
and welcome."

375
00:19:50,469 --> 00:19:54,166
You know, I heard
an interview with you
recently on the radio.

376
00:19:54,240 --> 00:19:56,572
You were giving it
from the back
of your Rolls-Royce.

377
00:19:56,642 --> 00:19:57,768
Bentley.

378
00:19:57,843 --> 00:19:58,901
On the phone.

379
00:19:58,978 --> 00:20:00,240
They said that
you were a person

380
00:20:00,312 --> 00:20:03,338
who defined
the age we live in.

381
00:20:03,415 --> 00:20:05,007
Really?
Mmm.

382
00:20:05,551 --> 00:20:07,143
You and Vidal Sassoon.

383
00:20:08,854 --> 00:20:11,823
But what made you
exceptional, they said,

384
00:20:11,891 --> 00:20:15,827
was that you were a person
who had achieved great fame

385
00:20:15,895 --> 00:20:19,262
without possessing
any discernible quality.

386
00:20:19,331 --> 00:20:20,559
How kind.
Mmm-hmm.

387
00:20:20,633 --> 00:20:23,932
And that you fly
around a great deal.

388
00:20:24,003 --> 00:20:26,301
Well, that's true.

389
00:20:27,206 --> 00:20:28,195
Why?

390
00:20:28,274 --> 00:20:29,764
I like to keep busy.

391
00:20:30,409 --> 00:20:31,808
Why?

392
00:20:31,877 --> 00:20:34,437
I find it
more interesting
than keeping still.

393
00:20:35,514 --> 00:20:37,448
You know,
you have very sad eyes.

394
00:20:38,150 --> 00:20:39,947
Do I?
Mmm.

395
00:20:40,019 --> 00:20:42,010
Has anyone told
you that before?

396
00:20:42,555 --> 00:20:43,817
No.

397
00:20:43,889 --> 00:20:45,550
Are you a sad person?

398
00:20:49,428 --> 00:20:51,988
Let's talk about
you a little bit.

399
00:20:52,064 --> 00:20:54,555
Of course, you feel more
comfortable asking questions.

400
00:20:54,633 --> 00:20:56,567
How right you are!

401
00:20:56,902 --> 00:20:58,631
<i>This is your</i>
<i>captain speaking.</i>

402
00:20:58,704 --> 00:20:59,693
<i>You may have</i>
<i>noticed we've begun</i>

403
00:20:59,772 --> 00:21:01,899
<i>our final descent</i>
<i>into Los Angeles.</i>

404
00:21:02,808 --> 00:21:05,868
<i>If you could please</i>
<i>return to your seats</i>
<i>and fasten your seat belts,</i>

405
00:21:05,945 --> 00:21:08,004
<i>we'll be landing</i>
<i>very shortly. Thank you.</i>

406
00:21:08,080 --> 00:21:10,378
CAROLINE: So how about you?
Where are you going?

407
00:21:10,449 --> 00:21:12,815
To meet Richard Nixon.

408
00:21:12,885 --> 00:21:14,113
Really?

409
00:21:15,788 --> 00:21:18,586
You know, they say he has
the most enormous head,

410
00:21:19,058 --> 00:21:20,616
but the sexiest voice.

411
00:21:20,693 --> 00:21:22,058
Where is he now?

412
00:21:22,328 --> 00:21:25,855
In some dark underground cave
licking his wounds?

413
00:21:26,732 --> 00:21:29,496
Actually, no.
In his rather smart
beachside villa

414
00:21:29,568 --> 00:21:30,626
in California.

415
00:21:30,703 --> 00:21:33,433
Really? Richard Nixon
in a beachside villa?

416
00:21:33,505 --> 00:21:35,097
How incongruous.

417
00:21:35,174 --> 00:21:37,142
You can come if you'd like.

418
00:21:37,643 --> 00:21:39,304
To meet Nixon?

419
00:21:40,045 --> 00:21:41,740
Why not?

420
00:21:43,115 --> 00:21:44,412
Are you sure?

421
00:21:47,453 --> 00:21:49,148
You know, I would love that.

422
00:21:49,221 --> 00:21:51,382
<i>PILOT. Cabin crew,</i>
<i>please prepare for arrival.</i>

423
00:21:51,457 --> 00:21:54,324
Well, I'll get
my office to call you
first thing in the morning

424
00:21:54,393 --> 00:21:56,953
and send a car with a phone.

425
00:21:57,029 --> 00:21:58,018
Oh.

426
00:22:00,466 --> 00:22:03,526
He did, too. Money no object.

427
00:22:03,602 --> 00:22:07,595
Everything glittered
and was golden.

428
00:22:07,673 --> 00:22:09,140
Well, on the outside.

429
00:22:09,208 --> 00:22:12,041
<i>Of course, what I didn't know</i>
<i>was that in the meantime,</i>

430
00:22:12,111 --> 00:22:14,272
<i>he'd gone to all</i>
<i>the major networks</i>

431
00:22:14,346 --> 00:22:16,814
<i>to try and get</i>
<i>interest in the interviews.</i>

432
00:22:17,349 --> 00:22:20,216
I'm sorry, David,
but we have a policy

433
00:22:20,285 --> 00:22:22,719
of not paying
for a news interview.

434
00:22:22,788 --> 00:22:25,951
Look, we love your work
as an entertainer.

435
00:22:26,025 --> 00:22:27,151
That <i>Guinness</i> show?

436
00:22:27,226 --> 00:22:28,716
Love it. You're a funny guy.

437
00:22:28,794 --> 00:22:30,989
But an interview like this?

438
00:22:31,063 --> 00:22:33,964
You're asking us to pay
a British talk show host

439
00:22:34,033 --> 00:22:36,263
to interview
an American president

440
00:22:36,335 --> 00:22:39,998
with absolutely no
editorial controls
whatsoever in return?

441
00:22:40,072 --> 00:22:42,040
Well, you can't say
it's not a fresh approach.

442
00:22:42,107 --> 00:22:43,836
I know you're very busy.

443
00:22:43,976 --> 00:22:45,910
I'm not gonna
keep you from it.

444
00:22:46,545 --> 00:22:48,137
Thank you for coming in.

445
00:22:48,213 --> 00:22:50,306
I'm gonna have to
get back to you.

446
00:22:50,382 --> 00:22:53,249
Okay, thank you so
much for your time.

447
00:22:53,318 --> 00:22:54,376
David, good luck.

448
00:22:54,453 --> 00:22:56,819
He never let on
to anyone at the time,

449
00:22:56,889 --> 00:22:58,083
not even me.
You know,
that would have meant...

450
00:22:58,991 --> 00:22:59,980
Thanks.

451
00:23:00,059 --> 00:23:03,620
<i>...admitting failure,</i>
<i>and David doesn't do failure.</i>

452
00:23:34,727 --> 00:23:36,661
FROST: There you are.

453
00:23:36,729 --> 00:23:39,220
See, you don't have
to do a thing yourself.

454
00:23:41,700 --> 00:23:44,567
(INDISTINCT)

455
00:23:58,550 --> 00:23:59,642
Well.

456
00:24:00,285 --> 00:24:01,445
You found it okay.

457
00:24:01,520 --> 00:24:02,646
Yes, thank you.

458
00:24:02,721 --> 00:24:03,881
Pleasure to meet you,
Mr. Frost.

459
00:24:03,956 --> 00:24:05,048
And you, sir.

460
00:24:05,124 --> 00:24:06,648
May I present
Caroline Cushing?

461
00:24:06,725 --> 00:24:07,783
Miss Cushing.

462
00:24:07,860 --> 00:24:09,953
Hello.
Your house is
very beautiful.

463
00:24:10,028 --> 00:24:11,188
Really. Very romantic.

464
00:24:11,263 --> 00:24:12,355
Well, thank you.

465
00:24:12,431 --> 00:24:14,262
And my producer, John Birt.

466
00:24:14,333 --> 00:24:15,857
Nice to meet you.
How do you do?

467
00:24:15,934 --> 00:24:19,370
This is Mr. Lazar,
and this is Jack Brennan.

468
00:24:19,438 --> 00:24:21,770
Now, Miss Cushing,
would you like
to take a tour,

469
00:24:21,840 --> 00:24:24,138
you know,
maybe stretch your legs
after your long journey?

470
00:24:24,209 --> 00:24:26,871
Yes, please.
I'd love that. Thank you.

471
00:24:27,913 --> 00:24:29,972
Come on in.
This is my office.

472
00:24:30,048 --> 00:24:34,178
Now, this is where Brezhnev
and I had our summit.

473
00:24:34,253 --> 00:24:38,622
Yeah. Brezhnev was there,
and Gromyko there,
Dobrynin there.

474
00:24:39,291 --> 00:24:42,783
We talked for
nine hours straight.

475
00:24:43,996 --> 00:24:47,488
After the meeting,
as a souvenir of the visit,

476
00:24:47,566 --> 00:24:51,832
I remember that we had
a Lincoln specially made.

477
00:24:51,904 --> 00:24:55,101
Dark blue,
cherry wood, leather.

478
00:24:55,174 --> 00:24:57,836
Well, we got inside
for the photographers,

479
00:24:57,910 --> 00:25:02,176
when the next thing you know,
he steps on the gas.

480
00:25:02,247 --> 00:25:06,980
Now, the first rule
of political life is

481
00:25:07,052 --> 00:25:11,489
you never let a president
get behind the wheel
of a car, ever.

482
00:25:11,557 --> 00:25:13,548
I mean, we're not
used to doing anything

483
00:25:13,625 --> 00:25:15,593
for ourselves,
let alone drive.

484
00:25:15,661 --> 00:25:18,858
And the Chairman, Jesus,
the way he put his foot down,

485
00:25:18,931 --> 00:25:21,695
my guess is
the last thing he drove was

486
00:25:21,767 --> 00:25:24,793
a tractor on some
Ukrainian potato farm.

487
00:25:26,705 --> 00:25:28,263
He crashed into curbs.

488
00:25:28,340 --> 00:25:29,830
He went over speed bumps.

489
00:25:29,908 --> 00:25:32,809
He went twice
around my whole estate.

490
00:25:32,878 --> 00:25:37,679
Finally, we ended up
at some remote point
on the coast,

491
00:25:37,749 --> 00:25:40,684
out there
overlooking the sea.

492
00:25:40,752 --> 00:25:44,950
He turns off the gas,
and he talks for two hours

493
00:25:45,023 --> 00:25:48,481
about his favorite subject,
steel mills.

494
00:25:48,560 --> 00:25:51,324
He said, "Mr. President,
most politicians

495
00:25:51,396 --> 00:25:54,092
"have tragedy
in their early lives."

496
00:25:55,000 --> 00:25:59,198
Well, I told him that
I lost two brothers
to tuberculosis.

497
00:25:59,271 --> 00:26:04,265
And he watched his father
die from the cancer
he caught in the steelworks.

498
00:26:05,177 --> 00:26:09,546
He was a sad man
and a noble adversary.

499
00:26:10,215 --> 00:26:12,581
I wouldn't want to
be a Russian leader.

500
00:26:13,085 --> 00:26:15,451
They never know when
they're being taped.

501
00:26:21,059 --> 00:26:22,890
Okay, I guess that's
it then, huh?

502
00:26:22,961 --> 00:26:24,758
Until March.
I look forward to it.

503
00:26:24,830 --> 00:26:26,695
Well, thank you,
Mr. President. So do I.

504
00:26:26,765 --> 00:26:28,392
You know,
it's a funny thing that

505
00:26:28,467 --> 00:26:32,164
I've never been
challenged to a duel before.

506
00:26:32,237 --> 00:26:33,499
I guess that's what this is.

507
00:26:33,572 --> 00:26:35,506
FROST: Yeah, well, not really.

508
00:26:36,575 --> 00:26:38,167
Of course it is.

509
00:26:40,312 --> 00:26:41,973
And I like that.

510
00:26:43,282 --> 00:26:47,218
No holds barred, eh?
No holds barred.

511
00:26:51,089 --> 00:26:55,253
Mr. Frost, there's still
the small matter of the...

512
00:26:56,762 --> 00:26:58,024
Of course.

513
00:26:59,464 --> 00:27:01,932
I do beg your pardon.

514
00:27:12,244 --> 00:27:17,511
Right. $200,000.

515
00:27:17,883 --> 00:27:20,750
I do hope that isn't coming
out of your own pocket.

516
00:27:20,819 --> 00:27:23,913
Well, believe me,
sir, I wish my pockets
were that deep.

517
00:27:24,923 --> 00:27:26,618
Made out in the name of?

518
00:27:26,692 --> 00:27:27,818
Irving Paul Lazar.

519
00:27:27,893 --> 00:27:29,724
Richard M. Nixon.

520
00:27:38,737 --> 00:27:39,863
Here you go.

521
00:27:41,173 --> 00:27:43,038
MANOLO: Okay, smile.

522
00:27:44,409 --> 00:27:47,674
There. Now you can
put that in your
apartment in New York,

523
00:27:47,746 --> 00:27:51,307
and all your liberal friends
can use it as a dartboard.

524
00:27:51,383 --> 00:27:55,080
Well, actually,
I'm living in Monte Carlo
at the moment.

525
00:27:55,153 --> 00:27:56,552
Really?

526
00:27:56,621 --> 00:27:58,452
Yes. Goodbye, Mr. President.

527
00:27:59,992 --> 00:28:02,927
Hey. Take my advice.

528
00:28:02,995 --> 00:28:04,553
You should marry that woman.

529
00:28:04,629 --> 00:28:07,860
Yes. Lovely, isn't she?

530
00:28:07,933 --> 00:28:10,902
More important than that,
she comes from Monaco.

531
00:28:10,969 --> 00:28:12,994
They pay no taxes there.

532
00:28:14,306 --> 00:28:16,240
Bye-bye.
Goodbye.

533
00:28:24,716 --> 00:28:26,377
I bet you it did.

534
00:28:26,451 --> 00:28:27,475
What?

535
00:28:27,552 --> 00:28:28,951
Come out of his own pocket.

536
00:28:29,021 --> 00:28:31,148
You know, he couldn't
look me in the eye.

537
00:28:31,223 --> 00:28:32,850
Well, I hear
the networks
aren't biting.

538
00:28:32,924 --> 00:28:35,017
Without the networks,
the ad agencies
don't want to know.

539
00:28:35,093 --> 00:28:36,321
So if you ask me,
there's a good chance

540
00:28:36,395 --> 00:28:37,555
this whole thing
may never happen.

541
00:28:37,629 --> 00:28:42,828
Really?
So that meeting we just had
might have cost him $200,000?

542
00:28:42,901 --> 00:28:43,993
Correct.

543
00:28:44,870 --> 00:28:48,328
Had I known that,
I would have offered
him a cup of tea.

544
00:28:48,807 --> 00:28:51,207
Say, did you
notice his shoes?

545
00:28:51,276 --> 00:28:52,300
No.

546
00:28:52,377 --> 00:28:55,869
Italian. No laces.
What do you think?

547
00:28:56,681 --> 00:28:59,081
My people tried to get me
to wear a pair like that.

548
00:28:59,151 --> 00:29:01,711
I think a man's shoes
should have laces, sir.

549
00:29:01,920 --> 00:29:02,944
You do?

550
00:29:03,021 --> 00:29:06,582
Yeah. Personally,
I find those Italian
shoes very effeminate.

551
00:29:08,126 --> 00:29:09,718
Yes, quite right.

552
00:29:12,597 --> 00:29:14,724
<i>NBC EXECUTIVE. I'm sorry,</i>
<i>David, but it's a no.</i>

553
00:29:14,800 --> 00:29:16,529
<i>Try to look at it</i>
<i>from our point of view.</i>

554
00:29:16,601 --> 00:29:19,536
<i>Why would an American network</i>
<i>hire a total outsider,</i>

555
00:29:19,604 --> 00:29:22,869
and someone who's already
had his own show canceled,
incidentally?

556
00:29:22,941 --> 00:29:24,465
I see. Well, I'm sorry
you feel this way.

557
00:29:24,543 --> 00:29:27,410
Obviously,
I think you're making
a terrible mistake.

558
00:29:30,015 --> 00:29:31,380
NBC.

559
00:29:32,818 --> 00:29:36,879
Well, that's
the networks out,
all of them.

560
00:29:38,457 --> 00:29:40,550
Well, that's the
end of that, then.

561
00:29:45,730 --> 00:29:47,527
I'm sorry, David.

562
00:29:48,200 --> 00:29:49,997
Not so fast.

563
00:29:51,403 --> 00:29:53,928
Where's your
adventurer's spirit?

564
00:29:54,005 --> 00:29:55,973
The idea is
we pay for the program

565
00:29:56,041 --> 00:30:01,069
and syndicate it
ourselves, completely
bypassing the networks.

566
00:30:01,146 --> 00:30:03,740
Just imagine it,
we'd be our own
network for the night.

567
00:30:03,815 --> 00:30:05,715
Hey, Bob.
FROST: How does that grab you?

568
00:30:05,784 --> 00:30:07,649
Hey, come on in.
David's on the phone.

569
00:30:07,719 --> 00:30:09,550
FROST: No, never been
done before.

570
00:30:09,621 --> 00:30:11,213
Historic stuff.

571
00:30:14,593 --> 00:30:17,687
Just think about it, okay?
And call me back.

572
00:30:18,330 --> 00:30:19,820
Yeah?
Yeah.

573
00:30:19,898 --> 00:30:22,924
David, I'd like you
to meet Jim Reston
and Bob Zelnick,

574
00:30:23,001 --> 00:30:24,195
our two prospective
corner men.

575
00:30:24,269 --> 00:30:25,361
Delighted to meet you.

576
00:30:25,437 --> 00:30:27,234
Come on in.
Make yourselves at home.

577
00:30:27,305 --> 00:30:28,636
Bob's been
Washington correspondent

578
00:30:28,707 --> 00:30:30,004
for Public Radio
for the past 10 years.

579
00:30:30,075 --> 00:30:32,270
Moving to ABC
in the new year.

580
00:30:32,344 --> 00:30:33,675
The general feeling, David,

581
00:30:33,745 --> 00:30:37,545
is that I have been
wasting my matinee idol
looks on radio.

582
00:30:38,183 --> 00:30:40,174
Jim here teaches
at the University
of North Carolina

583
00:30:40,252 --> 00:30:44,086
and is writing a book
about the criminal
dishonesty, corruption,

584
00:30:44,789 --> 00:30:47,223
paranoia and abuses of
power of Richard Nixon.

585
00:30:47,292 --> 00:30:48,759
Second on the subject.

586
00:30:48,827 --> 00:30:49,885
Fourth.

587
00:30:49,961 --> 00:30:52,020
Well, delighted to
have you both aboard.

588
00:30:52,097 --> 00:30:54,531
Actually, before I sign on,
I would like to hear

589
00:30:54,599 --> 00:30:57,466
what you were
hoping to achieve
with this interview.

590
00:30:58,069 --> 00:31:00,060
What I want to achieve?

591
00:31:00,138 --> 00:31:01,400
Yeah.

592
00:31:01,873 --> 00:31:05,570
Jim, well,
I've secured 12 taping days.

593
00:31:05,644 --> 00:31:07,578
That's close to 30 hours

594
00:31:07,646 --> 00:31:09,841
with the most compelling
and controversial politician

595
00:31:09,915 --> 00:31:11,678
of our times.

596
00:31:11,750 --> 00:31:13,217
Isn't that enough?

597
00:31:15,120 --> 00:31:16,451
Well, not for me.

598
00:31:17,789 --> 00:31:21,122
Look, I'd be giving up
a year of my life.
I'm leaving my family

599
00:31:21,193 --> 00:31:23,855
to work on
a subject matter
that means more

600
00:31:23,929 --> 00:31:25,624
than you can
probably imagine,

601
00:31:25,697 --> 00:31:26,789
and the idea
of doing all that

602
00:31:26,865 --> 00:31:30,301
without achieving what
I want to, personally,

603
00:31:30,368 --> 00:31:32,131
would be unthinkable to me.

604
00:31:32,204 --> 00:31:33,432
(INTERRUPTING)
FROST: No, all right.

605
00:31:34,172 --> 00:31:36,868
Well, what is it that
you want to achieve?

606
00:31:42,514 --> 00:31:45,483
I'd like to
give Richard Nixon
the trial he never had.

607
00:31:45,550 --> 00:31:48,815
Of course,
we'll be asking
difficult questions.

608
00:31:48,887 --> 00:31:50,548
Difficult questions.

609
00:31:51,489 --> 00:31:53,684
The man lost 21,000 Americans

610
00:31:53,758 --> 00:31:56,192
and a million Indo-Chinese
during his administration.

611
00:31:56,261 --> 00:31:59,059
He only escaped jail
because of Ford's pardon.

612
00:31:59,130 --> 00:32:02,429
Yes, but equally,
going after him
in some knee-jerk way,

613
00:32:02,500 --> 00:32:06,027
you know, assuming
he's a terrible guy,

614
00:32:06,104 --> 00:32:09,801
wouldn't that only create
more sympathy for him
than anything else?

615
00:32:09,874 --> 00:32:11,341
(SIGHS) You know...

616
00:32:13,545 --> 00:32:15,342
Right now,
I submit it's impossible

617
00:32:15,413 --> 00:32:18,905
to feel anything
close to sympathy
for Richard Nixon.

618
00:32:18,984 --> 00:32:21,111
He devalued the presidency,

619
00:32:21,186 --> 00:32:24,781
and he left the country
that elected him in trauma.

620
00:32:25,924 --> 00:32:29,621
The American people
need a conviction,
pure and simple.

621
00:32:29,694 --> 00:32:32,390
The integrity of
our political system,

622
00:32:32,464 --> 00:32:38,300
of democracy as an idea,
entirely depends on it.

623
00:32:38,370 --> 00:32:40,668
And if in years to come,
people look back

624
00:32:40,739 --> 00:32:42,138
and say it was
in this interview

625
00:32:42,207 --> 00:32:43,799
that Richard Nixon
exonerated himself,

626
00:32:43,875 --> 00:32:46,070
that would be
the worst crime of all.

627
00:32:55,787 --> 00:32:58,847
Did you know that
Mike Wallace is doing
a piece on this?

628
00:33:00,792 --> 00:33:03,488
And that in the bars around
Capitol Hill and Georgetown

629
00:33:03,561 --> 00:33:05,324
this entire project is a joke?

630
00:33:05,397 --> 00:33:08,059
ZELNICK: Come on.
Jim, come on.

631
00:33:08,133 --> 00:33:10,465
Thanks for that, Jim.

632
00:33:11,503 --> 00:33:13,835
Could you give us
a couple of minutes?

633
00:33:21,079 --> 00:33:22,569
You're unbelievable.
I'm sorry, Bob.

634
00:33:22,647 --> 00:33:24,877
You know, Jim,
I went way out
on a limb for you.

635
00:33:24,949 --> 00:33:26,541
I mean, some of us
actually want this job.

636
00:33:26,618 --> 00:33:28,108
I want it, too,
if it's done right.

637
00:33:28,186 --> 00:33:29,983
Well, how do you know
they're not
gonna do it right?

638
00:33:30,055 --> 00:33:31,283
Little Lord Fauntleroy
in there?

639
00:33:31,356 --> 00:33:32,550
Sympathy for Richard Nixon?

640
00:33:32,624 --> 00:33:34,251
What the...
He's full of shit, man!

641
00:33:34,326 --> 00:33:35,850
How do you know that?

642
00:33:38,063 --> 00:33:41,032
Is Mike Wallace
doing a piece on this?

643
00:33:42,300 --> 00:33:43,324
Apparently.

644
00:33:43,401 --> 00:33:45,028
Why didn't you tell me?

645
00:33:45,770 --> 00:33:47,169
It isn't relevant.

646
00:33:48,273 --> 00:33:52,004
What's the angle?
"British talk show host,

647
00:33:52,777 --> 00:33:56,508
"good with actresses,
not so good with
stonewalling presidents."

648
00:33:56,815 --> 00:33:58,612
That's the general idea, yeah.

649
00:33:58,683 --> 00:33:59,877
Right.

650
00:34:01,119 --> 00:34:03,849
It's hard not to feel
a little insulted by that.

651
00:34:05,557 --> 00:34:08,025
Well, Bob's obviously a pro.

652
00:34:08,093 --> 00:34:09,287
What are we gonna
do about Reston?

653
00:34:09,361 --> 00:34:10,919
Well, the man's an idiot.
He's overemotional.

654
00:34:10,995 --> 00:34:12,257
Send him home.

655
00:34:13,665 --> 00:34:15,633
Well, I think
he should stay.
Why?

656
00:34:15,700 --> 00:34:18,999
I liked his passion.

657
00:34:19,070 --> 00:34:21,061
He will drive us
all bloody mad.

658
00:34:21,606 --> 00:34:24,336
Well, maybe, but sometimes
being out of your comfort zone

659
00:34:24,409 --> 00:34:27,071
is a good thing, I'm told.

660
00:34:28,113 --> 00:34:29,375
He stays.

661
00:34:39,991 --> 00:34:44,087
<i>I took my seat</i>
<i>next to Mrs. Mao</i>
<i>at the banquet table.</i>

662
00:34:44,729 --> 00:34:49,428
<i>Now, one of the challenges</i>
<i>of life as a president</i>

663
00:34:50,135 --> 00:34:57,064
<i>is the endless round</i>
<i>of cocktail parties,</i>
<i>social engagements, banquets.</i>

664
00:34:57,809 --> 00:34:59,800
<i>And people who</i>
<i>know me would tell you</i>

665
00:34:59,878 --> 00:35:04,110
<i>that small talk is not one of</i>
<i>my strong suits, either. No.</i>

666
00:35:04,783 --> 00:35:07,877
<i>Particularly not in Mandarin.</i>

667
00:35:10,889 --> 00:35:15,883
<i>So Mrs. Mao and I,</i>
<i>we just, well, you know,</i>
<i>stared at one another.</i>

668
00:35:17,028 --> 00:35:21,328
<i>And then across the table,</i>
<i>Mrs. Nixon and</i>
<i>Chairman Mao himself, well,</i>

669
00:35:22,167 --> 00:35:24,533
<i>they stared</i>
<i>at one another, too.</i>

670
00:35:24,602 --> 00:35:27,469
<i>And then further down,</i>
<i>Dr. Kissinger</i>

671
00:35:27,539 --> 00:35:30,372
<i>and their</i>
<i>foreign minister, well,</i>

672
00:35:30,875 --> 00:35:33,901
<i>you're getting</i>
<i>the picture now.</i>

673
00:35:38,583 --> 00:35:40,551
I can't stand it, Jack!

674
00:35:41,853 --> 00:35:47,018
Reducing the presidency
to a series
of banal anecdotes.

675
00:35:47,192 --> 00:35:50,025
I feel like
a circus animal
doing tricks.

676
00:35:50,228 --> 00:35:51,991
And I thought
I made it clear!

677
00:35:52,063 --> 00:35:56,591
I didn't want to take
any questions
on Watergate, damn it!

678
00:35:58,036 --> 00:36:00,402
Soon as it came
to question time,

679
00:36:00,472 --> 00:36:05,102
all those sons of bitches
ever want to hear about
is Watergate!

680
00:36:05,210 --> 00:36:09,670
It's as if all
my other achievements
have ceased to exist.

681
