We have to take a break.
Tape change.

1145
00:58:16,173 --> 00:58:18,971
Oh. Okay, how's that?
You getting what you need?

1146
00:58:19,042 --> 00:58:20,304
It's fantastic.

1147
00:58:20,377 --> 00:58:21,969
Good. Good. Thank you.

1148
00:58:23,547 --> 00:58:24,707
Excuse me. One moment, sir.

1149
00:58:24,781 --> 00:58:26,874
NIXON: Yeah, sure.
Take your time.

1150
00:58:27,250 --> 00:58:29,218
What are you doing, David?
You've got to
stop him rambling.

1151
00:58:29,286 --> 00:58:31,481
It's all right.
These are just
introductory exchanges.

1152
00:58:31,555 --> 00:58:33,022
But this session
only lasts two hours.

1153
00:58:33,089 --> 00:58:35,785
Nearly half of it's gone,
and we're wasting
valuable material, okay?

1154
00:58:35,859 --> 00:58:38,123
The moment that he made
the decision to resign,

1155
00:58:38,195 --> 00:58:39,492
we should be scoring
points with that stuff.

1156
00:58:39,563 --> 00:58:40,723
Want me to switch to Vietnam?

1157
00:58:40,797 --> 00:58:42,287
No. No.
We've got to
get something

1158
00:58:42,365 --> 00:58:44,094
out of that
resignation night.
All right?

1159
00:58:44,167 --> 00:58:47,728
That was Nixon at
his lowest point,
a total wreck. On his knees?

1160
00:58:47,804 --> 00:58:50,295
Praying with Kissinger?
Come on, you can nail
him with that stuff.

1161
00:58:50,373 --> 00:58:51,738
Listen, was that okay?

1162
00:58:51,808 --> 00:58:53,105
Perfect, sir.

1163
00:58:53,176 --> 00:58:55,838
It didn't sound too
arrogant or self-serving?

1164
00:58:55,912 --> 00:58:59,404
Not at all.
You sounded controlled,
even-handed, statesmanlike.

1165
00:58:59,482 --> 00:59:00,676
Good.

1166
00:59:00,750 --> 00:59:01,910
Now continue
exactly the same way.

1167
00:59:01,985 --> 00:59:03,885
Long answers.
Control the space.

1168
00:59:03,954 --> 00:59:04,943
Don't let him in.

1169
00:59:05,021 --> 00:59:06,283
Okay, got you.

1170
00:59:09,526 --> 00:59:11,551
DAVIS: Set. And roll.

1171
00:59:16,399 --> 00:59:21,462
We're coming
back on camera three
in four, three, two and...

1172
00:59:23,907 --> 00:59:27,968
Reading the account
of those extraordinary
final days,

1173
00:59:28,044 --> 00:59:30,512
it seems your most
emotional moment came

1174
00:59:30,580 --> 00:59:33,913
in that
heart-to-heart you had
with Henry Kissinger.

1175
00:59:33,984 --> 00:59:37,613
Was that perhaps
the most emotional moment
of your career?

1176
00:59:38,088 --> 00:59:39,680
RESTON: Good, good.
<i>NIXON: Yes.</i>

1177
00:59:40,423 --> 00:59:45,725
I would say it was
about as emotional
a moment as I've ever had.

1178
00:59:47,898 --> 00:59:50,025
Except, well,
you know,
it's hard to say

1179
00:59:50,100 --> 00:59:52,193
what is the most
emotional moment,

1180
00:59:52,269 --> 00:59:54,863
because each is different.

1181
00:59:55,305 --> 00:59:58,399
<i>I remember the day</i>
<i>Eisenhower died.</i>

1182
00:59:58,475 --> 00:59:59,772
For God's sake.

1183
00:59:59,843 --> 01:00:04,109
<i>And the day I walked</i>
<i>my eldest daughter</i>
<i>Tricia down the aisle.</i>

1184
01:00:04,180 --> 01:00:06,876
And the day during
the impeachment hearings

1185
01:00:06,950 --> 01:00:10,579
when Julie,
that's my youngest,
she came into my office,

1186
01:00:10,654 --> 01:00:15,148
she threw her arms around me,
she kissed me.
She cried, you know?

1187
01:00:15,225 --> 01:00:18,126
And she so seldom cries.

1188
01:00:18,328 --> 01:00:20,660
<i>She said, ''Daddy, you're</i>
<i>the finest man I know. ''</i>

1189
01:00:20,730 --> 01:00:22,721
"Daddy, you're
the finest man I know"?

1190
01:00:23,199 --> 01:00:26,691
"And whatever you do,
I will support you.

1191
01:00:27,771 --> 01:00:32,105
"You just gotta
go through the fire,
you know, a little longer."

1192
01:00:34,477 --> 01:00:36,240
This is beautiful.

1193
01:00:36,313 --> 01:00:39,476
So Kissinger and I were
in the Lincoln Sitting Room,

1194
01:00:39,549 --> 01:00:42,541
and together we began
to reminisce

1195
01:00:42,619 --> 01:00:46,453
about some of
the great decisions that
we'd participated in.

1196
01:00:46,523 --> 01:00:49,720
There was China,
the Soviet Union,

1197
01:00:49,793 --> 01:00:52,318
the peace settlement
in Vietnam.

1198
01:00:52,395 --> 01:00:56,422
<i>Now, let me</i>
<i>tell you something that</i>
<i>I never told anybody.</i>

1199
01:00:56,499 --> 01:01:00,936
Whenever I have had
a really tough
decision to make...

1200
01:01:01,271 --> 01:01:04,035
Now, we were in
the Lincoln Sitting Room
at that time.

1201
01:01:04,107 --> 01:01:07,804
I have come into this room
for the purpose of praying.

1202
01:01:08,845 --> 01:01:12,713
"Now, Henry,
I'm a Quaker.
You're a Jew.

1203
01:01:12,782 --> 01:01:14,750
"Neither of us is
particularly orthodox,

1204
01:01:14,818 --> 01:01:17,844
"but I'd like to think
that each of us
in our own way

1205
01:01:17,921 --> 01:01:20,913
"has a deep
religious sensitivity.

1206
01:01:20,991 --> 01:01:26,088
"So if you don't mind,
could we just have a moment
of silent prayer?"

1207
01:01:26,162 --> 01:01:30,394
So we knelt down.
Now, this was in front
of that table where

1208
01:01:30,467 --> 01:01:34,631
Lincoln signed
the Emancipation
Proclamation.

1209
01:01:34,704 --> 01:01:38,140
And then after a few moments,
we both got up again,
and Henry says...

1210
01:01:38,241 --> 01:01:39,799
Is there... I'm sorry.

1211
01:01:39,943 --> 01:01:41,103
Is there a problem?

1212
01:01:41,177 --> 01:01:42,201
That's time.

1213
01:01:42,779 --> 01:01:44,906
We're over two hours.

1214
01:01:44,981 --> 01:01:47,074
Really? So soon?

1215
01:01:47,784 --> 01:01:50,753
Well, Mr. President,
I gather our time is up.

1216
01:01:50,954 --> 01:01:52,751
Gee, now, that's a pity.

1217
01:01:52,822 --> 01:01:55,313
You know,
I was beginning
to enjoy that.

1218
01:01:59,295 --> 01:02:01,661
That was terrific,
both of you.

1219
01:02:01,731 --> 01:02:03,096
We're getting some
great material.

1220
01:02:03,166 --> 01:02:04,531
You know,
it's so funny, too,

1221
01:02:04,601 --> 01:02:08,037
because I was expecting
questions on Vietnam.

1222
01:02:08,104 --> 01:02:10,595
And we prepared for that,
hadn't we, Jack?

1223
01:02:10,673 --> 01:02:12,072
Yes, so did I.

1224
01:02:12,142 --> 01:02:15,270
I guess we
just got caught up,
you know, reminiscing.

1225
01:02:15,345 --> 01:02:16,369
Indeed.

1226
01:02:16,446 --> 01:02:18,710
So, day after tomorrow,
10:00, right?

1227
01:02:18,782 --> 01:02:19,874
Yes, indeed.

1228
01:02:19,949 --> 01:02:21,644
I look forward to it.
Bye-bye.

1229
01:02:29,125 --> 01:02:31,184
There's no need
to say anything.

1230
01:02:37,767 --> 01:02:39,894
REPORTER 1 : Mr. President!
REPORTER 2: Mr. President!

1231
01:02:40,136 --> 01:02:42,104
(REPORTERS CLAMORING)

1232
01:02:42,972 --> 01:02:44,234
REPORTER 3: Mr. President!

1233
01:02:44,307 --> 01:02:45,638
REPORTER 4:
Mr. President, please!

1234
01:02:46,643 --> 01:02:47,871
(WHISPERING)
What are you
gonna tell him?

1235
01:02:47,944 --> 01:02:49,639
I'm gonna tell him
he's gotta get involved.

1236
01:02:49,712 --> 01:02:51,543
He's gotta be able
to shut him up.
Shh.

1237
01:02:51,614 --> 01:02:54,640
David, we have some
fundamental problems in
our approach that I think...

1238
01:02:54,717 --> 01:02:56,116
Don't worry, Bob.
I'm on it.

1239
01:02:56,186 --> 01:02:57,210
We can use some of
the Kissinger stuff.

1240
01:02:57,287 --> 01:02:59,016
Yeah, but we need
to discuss it sooner
rather than later...

1241
01:02:59,089 --> 01:03:00,454
Look,
I'm disappointed, too.

1242
01:03:00,523 --> 01:03:03,253
But I wonder,
could we possibly spare
the post-mortem for now?

1243
01:03:03,326 --> 01:03:05,385
I don't mean to minimize it.
It's just I've got to
get back to LA

1244
01:03:05,462 --> 01:03:06,861
to meet some people
from Weed Eater.

1245
01:03:06,930 --> 01:03:08,761
Thanks, everyone!
Great work!

1246
01:03:08,832 --> 01:03:11,027
Marv, Lloyd, great day.
Bye, David.

1247
01:03:11,101 --> 01:03:13,968
I'll see you soon.
God bless!

1248
01:03:17,006 --> 01:03:19,406
What the hell
is Weed Eater?

1249
01:03:19,709 --> 01:03:21,939
It's a horticultural
mechanism.

1250
01:03:22,011 --> 01:03:23,035
One of our sponsors.

1251
01:03:23,113 --> 01:03:24,478
What happened to Xerox?

1252
01:03:24,547 --> 01:03:26,811
What about
General Motors
or IBM?

1253
01:03:26,883 --> 01:03:29,943
I gather that not all of
the blue-chip accounts
came through.

1254
01:03:30,019 --> 01:03:32,214
We do have Alpo.

1255
01:03:32,288 --> 01:03:33,687
Dog food?

1256
01:03:33,756 --> 01:03:36,122
(STUTTERING) Wait, John.
We're already taping.

1257
01:03:36,626 --> 01:03:38,321
So we're close, right?
We're very close?

1258
01:03:38,394 --> 01:03:39,827
That's probably a question
you should ask David.

1259
01:03:39,896 --> 01:03:41,761
Are we close, John?

1260
01:03:44,667 --> 01:03:46,760
I believe we're at 30%.

1261
01:03:47,537 --> 01:03:49,027
To go? Or 30% sold?

1262
01:03:49,105 --> 01:03:51,801
Again, that's probably
a question you should...

1263
01:03:52,876 --> 01:03:54,468
Sold, 30% sold.

1264
01:03:55,178 --> 01:03:56,702
Jesus...

1265
01:03:56,846 --> 01:03:58,404
I thought
we were practically
fully financed.

1266
01:03:58,481 --> 01:04:01,609
We were. But the financing
was always conditional
on advertising sales,

1267
01:04:01,684 --> 01:04:03,379
and no one predicted
that they'd fall apart
like this.

1268
01:04:03,453 --> 01:04:05,353
Well, why have
they fallen apart?
Based on what?

1269
01:04:05,421 --> 01:04:08,219
Credibility of the project.
What else are advertising
sales based on?

1270
01:04:08,291 --> 01:04:10,452
Listen,
I understand your concern.

1271
01:04:10,527 --> 01:04:13,724
But could I ask you
to go a little easier on David
over the next couple of days,

1272
01:04:13,796 --> 01:04:16,264
bearing in mind
the extraordinary pressure
that he's under?

1273
01:04:16,332 --> 01:04:19,824
'Cause at the moment,
he's effectively paying
for all this himself.

1274
01:04:19,903 --> 01:04:23,566
So he's in it
for a lot more than
just his reputation.

1275
01:04:23,907 --> 01:04:25,204
And we're not?

1276
01:04:32,282 --> 01:04:35,877
<i>FROST. You seemed</i>
<i>very confident last time.</i>

1277
01:04:35,952 --> 01:04:38,887
<i>I don't understand.</i>
<i>Why this sudden</i>
<i>change of heart?</i>

1278
01:04:38,955 --> 01:04:41,515
All right,
this is just madness.
It's Richard Nixon.

1279
01:04:41,591 --> 01:04:45,823
These interviews
will do mid-30s
audience share, minimum.

1280
01:04:45,895 --> 01:04:52,528
Jimmy! Yes.
Yes, back again, like
the proverbial bad penny.

1281
01:04:52,602 --> 01:04:54,160
Look, I hate to do
this to a friend,

1282
01:04:54,237 --> 01:04:57,468
and I know you're already in
for more than I asked for,

1283
01:04:57,540 --> 01:05:00,976
but I need you to dig
a little deeper.

1284
01:05:02,512 --> 01:05:04,673
I'm right up against it now.

1285
01:05:08,251 --> 01:05:11,448
So, I had
a chance to review
yesterday's tapes.

1286
01:05:11,521 --> 01:05:12,749
And?

1287
01:05:12,822 --> 01:05:16,849
Honestly?
Far too soft, David.

1288
01:05:16,926 --> 01:05:19,019
Go on. Beat me, John.
Beat me with a stick.

1289
01:05:19,095 --> 01:05:22,087
Look. No, I'm serious.

1290
01:05:22,165 --> 01:05:24,565
You have got to make it
more uncomfortable for him.

1291
01:05:24,634 --> 01:05:27,364
You can start by
sitting forward.
You've gotta attack more.

1292
01:05:27,437 --> 01:05:29,029
If he starts
tailing off, bang,

1293
01:05:29,105 --> 01:05:30,504
jump in with
another question.

1294
01:05:30,573 --> 01:05:32,598
Don't trade
generalizations.

1295
01:05:32,675 --> 01:05:33,699
Be specific.

1296
01:05:33,776 --> 01:05:36,870
And above all, don't let
him give these self-serving,
23-minute homilies.

1297
01:05:36,946 --> 01:05:37,970
Right.
And keep your distance

1298
01:05:38,047 --> 01:05:39,309
before the tape
starts running.

1299
01:05:39,382 --> 01:05:40,679
He was toying
with you yesterday.

1300
01:05:40,750 --> 01:05:43,014
All that shit about <i>Ben-Hur</i>
and struggling to raise
the money.

1301
01:05:43,086 --> 01:05:47,147
Those are mind games.
Don't engage.

1302
01:05:47,223 --> 01:05:50,681
Never forget,
you are in there
with a major operator.

1303
01:05:51,928 --> 01:05:53,327
Got it.

1304
01:05:58,534 --> 01:05:59,933
(NIXON CLEARS THROAT)

1305
01:06:00,603 --> 01:06:01,627
Ah.

1306
01:06:02,472 --> 01:06:04,406
The Grand Inquisitor!

1307
01:06:05,575 --> 01:06:08,009
No, just your friendly
neighborhood confidant.

1308
01:06:09,112 --> 01:06:10,238
(GLASS SMASHING)

1309
01:06:12,882 --> 01:06:14,975
It's okay.
We just blew a bulb.

1310
01:06:15,752 --> 01:06:18,243
NIXON: This is why I got
all these Secret Service
guys around.

1311
01:06:18,321 --> 01:06:19,686
There's nothing
to worry about.

1312
01:06:19,756 --> 01:06:23,123
As a president,
you get used to
this kind of stuff.

1313
01:06:23,293 --> 01:06:26,785
DAVIS: Ed, we gotta
get in here and change
out this 750, ASAP.

1314
01:06:32,235 --> 01:06:33,896
(WHISPERING)
Focus, sir.
Yeah.

1315
01:06:36,472 --> 01:06:40,101
Okay, we are back.
Okay, take it
on my count.

1316
01:06:40,943 --> 01:06:43,878
Okay, stand by
to roll tape.
30 seconds.

1317
01:06:44,180 --> 01:06:45,408
DAVIS: Settling.

1318
01:06:45,481 --> 01:06:47,142
You have a pleasant
evening last night?

1319
01:06:47,216 --> 01:06:48,808
Yes, thank you.

1320
01:06:56,959 --> 01:06:59,257
Did you do
any fornicating?

1321
01:06:59,529 --> 01:07:02,555
David, we're starting
with camera two in four,

1322
01:07:02,632 --> 01:07:03,621
(CLEARS THROAT)

1323
01:07:03,700 --> 01:07:05,895
three, two and...

1324
01:07:10,506 --> 01:07:13,737
Mr. President,
you came to office
promising peace,

1325
01:07:13,810 --> 01:07:15,801
but no sooner
did you get into
the White House

1326
01:07:15,878 --> 01:07:20,315
than US involvement
in Vietnam deepened
and the war was prolonged

1327
01:07:20,383 --> 01:07:21,975
with calamitous
consequences.

1328
01:07:22,051 --> 01:07:25,509
Did you feel that you'd
betrayed the people
that had elected you?

1329
01:07:25,588 --> 01:07:29,354
Well, Vietnam
was not my war.

1330
01:07:29,425 --> 01:07:31,086
It was my inheritance.

1331
01:07:31,160 --> 01:07:33,025
<i>And it looked to me...</i>
Jump in.

1332
01:07:33,096 --> 01:07:36,122
...as if the reason
for our being there

1333
01:07:36,199 --> 01:07:40,898
had perhaps not been
adequately understood
by the American people.

1334
01:07:41,304 --> 01:07:43,329
It seemed to me
they hadn't realized

1335
01:07:43,406 --> 01:07:48,605
how important
a test this was
of American credibility.

1336
01:07:49,312 --> 01:07:51,337
The whole world
was watching to see

1337
01:07:51,414 --> 01:07:54,440
if we have the character
to see it through.

1338
01:07:54,517 --> 01:07:57,281
Now, look,
I could have bugged out.
I could have.

1339
01:07:57,353 --> 01:08:00,015
I could have blamed it
on my predecessors.

1340
01:08:00,089 --> 01:08:02,580
I could have
pulled the troops
out of Vietnam early,

1341
01:08:02,658 --> 01:08:04,990
and very possibly,
I would have won

1342
01:08:05,061 --> 01:08:08,292
some Scandinavian peace prize
into the bargain.

1343
01:08:08,364 --> 01:08:10,025
But I believed
in the cause.

1344
01:08:10,099 --> 01:08:15,435
And sometimes, you know,
what you believe in,
it's the harder path.

1345
01:08:15,505 --> 01:08:20,340
You might even say that
I was the last casualty
of the Vietnam War.

1346
01:08:20,410 --> 01:08:23,174
Yeah, tell that
to the paraplegics.

1347
01:08:23,279 --> 01:08:24,610
Come on, David,
Cambodia.

1348
01:08:24,680 --> 01:08:27,843
And Cambodia?
An invasion which everybody
advised you against.

1349
01:08:27,917 --> 01:08:30,943
All the CIA
and Pentagon intelligence
suggested it would fail.

1350
01:08:31,020 --> 01:08:32,112
So why did you do it?

1351
01:08:32,188 --> 01:08:33,246
Well, first of all,

1352
01:08:33,322 --> 01:08:39,750
as a result of
our incursion into Cambodia,
we picked up 22,000 rifles,

1353
01:08:39,829 --> 01:08:44,323
15 million rounds
of ammunition,
150,000 rockets, mortars.

1354
01:08:44,400 --> 01:08:46,630
That's all belonging
to the North Vietnamese,

1355
01:08:46,702 --> 01:08:49,728
which would only otherwise
have been directed

1356
01:08:49,806 --> 01:08:51,933
right onto
American soldiers.

1357
01:08:52,008 --> 01:08:55,273
But one of
the principal justifications
you gave for the incursion

1358
01:08:55,344 --> 01:08:57,005
was the supposed
existence of

1359
01:08:57,079 --> 01:09:01,982
the "headquarters of
the entire Communist military
operation in South Vietnam,"

1360
01:09:02,051 --> 01:09:05,817
a sort of "bamboo Pentagon"
which proved
not to exist at all.

1361
01:09:05,888 --> 01:09:07,549
No, no. Wait a minute
there. No, I was...
And by sending...

1362
01:09:07,623 --> 01:09:10,854
And by sending B-52s
to carpet bomb a country,

1363
01:09:10,927 --> 01:09:13,487
wiping out
whole civilian areas,

1364
01:09:13,563 --> 01:09:16,589
you end up radicalizing
a once moderate people,

1365
01:09:16,666 --> 01:09:19,260
uniting them in
anti-American sentiment

1366
01:09:19,402 --> 01:09:21,996
<i>and creating a monster</i>
<i>in the Khmer Rouge</i>

1367
01:09:22,071 --> 01:09:23,402
<i>that would lead</i>
<i>to civil war...</i>

1368
01:09:23,473 --> 01:09:25,134
All right!
<i>...and genocide.</i>

1369
01:09:25,274 --> 01:09:26,741
Yes, good, good, good.
There it is.

1370
01:09:26,809 --> 01:09:27,969
Okay, run VT.

1371
01:09:28,044 --> 01:09:29,033
Roll tape.

1372
01:10:25,668 --> 01:10:26,896
Well, sir,
I'm sure you'd agree,

1373
01:10:26,969 --> 01:10:29,028
some pretty
stirring images there.

1374
01:10:29,105 --> 01:10:34,873
Look, it was never US policy
to kill civilians.
That's the enemy's way.

1375
01:10:34,944 --> 01:10:35,933
Well, I'm not suggesting...

1376
01:10:36,012 --> 01:10:37,070
And if you're
asking the question

1377
01:10:37,146 --> 01:10:41,242
do I regret the casualties
on both sides in the war,
yeah, sure, of course I do.

1378
01:10:41,317 --> 01:10:43,376
Let me tell you something.
It can just wear you down.

1379
01:10:43,452 --> 01:10:45,386
Well, all right, sir,
when you are faced
with someone who...

1380
01:10:45,454 --> 01:10:47,513
But whenever
I have had my doubts,

1381
01:10:47,590 --> 01:10:49,717
I remembered
the construction worker
in Philadelphia,

1382
01:10:49,792 --> 01:10:51,020
because he came up to me

1383
01:10:51,093 --> 01:10:54,654
and he said, "Sir,
I got only one criticism
of that Cambodia thing.

1384
01:10:54,730 --> 01:10:56,459
"If you'd gone in earlier,

1385
01:10:56,532 --> 01:10:58,295
"you might have
captured the gun

1386
01:10:58,367 --> 01:11:00,392
"that killed my boy
three months ago."

1387
01:11:00,469 --> 01:11:03,461
So you're asking me,
do I regret
going into Cambodia?

1388
01:11:03,539 --> 01:11:05,803
No! I don't.
You know what?

1389
01:11:05,875 --> 01:11:08,935
I wish I'd gone in
sooner and harder.

1390
01:11:09,011 --> 01:11:10,069
SAWYER: Got him.
Safe!

1391
01:11:16,552 --> 01:11:21,421
It was horrifying.
It was horrifying.
And he was so confident.

1392
01:11:21,557 --> 01:11:23,650
(REPORTERS CLAMORING)

1393
01:11:24,427 --> 01:11:26,861
REPORTER:
What are you gonna say
about Watergate?

1394
01:11:27,196 --> 01:11:30,495
Sorry, boys,
just all talked out,
you know?

1395
01:11:37,239 --> 01:11:38,638
Better?

1396
01:11:42,244 --> 01:11:44,337
It was.
Unquestionably better.

1397
01:11:49,785 --> 01:11:51,013
What's next?

1398
01:11:51,654 --> 01:11:52,882
Foreign policy.

1399
01:11:55,424 --> 01:12:00,487
Great. Russia, China,
the big power stuff.

1400
01:12:00,563 --> 01:12:02,861
Yeah, so?

1401
01:12:02,932 --> 01:12:04,695
So if he beats him up
like that on Vietnam,

1402
01:12:04,767 --> 01:12:07,668
imagine what he's gonna do
with his real achievements.

1403
01:12:07,737 --> 01:12:09,034
(RESTON LAUGHS)

1404
01:12:10,272 --> 01:12:12,638
It ain't gonna be pretty.

1405
01:12:12,708 --> 01:12:15,438
The answer was
grow by six inches.

1406
01:12:15,511 --> 01:12:18,412
It was agony to watch.

1407
01:12:19,181 --> 01:12:22,082
Now, that's when
Khrushchev called me,
begging me to intervene.

1408
01:12:22,151 --> 01:12:24,176
You see, he and Mao
didn't get along,

1409
01:12:24,253 --> 01:12:26,585
and Khrushchev
knew that the Chairman

1410
01:12:26,656 --> 01:12:28,647
would talk to me,
no one else.

1411
01:12:28,724 --> 01:12:33,491
You see, I was the only one
that Mao would trust
personally, man-to-man.

1412
01:12:33,562 --> 01:12:36,087
When David tried to
lay a finger on him,

1413
01:12:36,165 --> 01:12:38,531
Nixon made mincemeat
out of him.

1414
01:12:39,502 --> 01:12:41,197
ZELNICK:
What "revolution," David?

1415
01:12:41,270 --> 01:12:43,067
You just let
Richard Nixon claim

1416
01:12:43,139 --> 01:12:45,369
the country was in
a state of revolution?

1417
01:12:45,441 --> 01:12:48,706
What, with protestors
"bombing" and "assaulting"
police officers?

1418
01:12:48,778 --> 01:12:50,006
That's not how
I remember it.

1419
01:12:50,079 --> 01:12:53,014
What I remember
is people protesting
peacefully and legitimately

1420
01:12:53,082 --> 01:12:54,242
against the Vietnam War!

1421
01:12:54,316 --> 01:12:55,874
That's what I remember.
Music off, please. Off.

1422
01:12:55,951 --> 01:12:58,647
By the end, wiretapping
students and breaking
into journalists' homes

1423
01:12:58,721 --> 01:13:00,951
was beginning to sound
like a rational response.

1424
01:13:01,023 --> 01:13:02,388
Well, I'm sorry
you feel this way,

1425
01:13:02,458 --> 01:13:04,551
but I simply cannot
share your view.

1426
01:13:04,627 --> 01:13:05,719
About what exactly?

1427
01:13:05,795 --> 01:13:07,160
About any of it, frankly!

1428
01:13:07,229 --> 01:13:09,857
I thought today was
a huge improvement.

1429
01:13:09,932 --> 01:13:10,956
Are you nuts?

1430
01:13:11,033 --> 01:13:13,024
Let me tell you how
bad things were today.

1431
01:13:13,102 --> 01:13:16,128
After the taping finished,
I overheard two members
of the crew say

1432
01:13:16,205 --> 01:13:18,571
they never voted for him
when they had the chance,

1433
01:13:18,641 --> 01:13:22,042
but if he ran
for office again today,
he'd get their support.

1434
01:13:22,111 --> 01:13:24,841
You're making him
look presidential,
for Christ's sake!

1435
01:13:24,914 --> 01:13:27,439
And forget about
the trivia, David.

1436
01:13:27,516 --> 01:13:30,383
Who cares whether Nixon
took the White House bed
to Europe

1437
01:13:30,453 --> 01:13:32,284
when he traveled?
I do!

1438
01:13:32,354 --> 01:13:34,015
Well, it's irrelevant!

1439
01:13:34,090 --> 01:13:37,787
And it's just
the sort of banal anecdote
that would distract a talk...

1440
01:13:39,128 --> 01:13:40,356
A what?

1441
01:13:43,332 --> 01:13:45,232
Go on. No, say it.

1442
01:13:45,301 --> 01:13:47,792
What, you were gonna
say "talk show host"?

1443
01:13:49,138 --> 01:13:51,572
Yeah. Yeah, I was.

1444
01:13:59,415 --> 01:14:03,681
All right, look,
it's useless me trying
to answer your points.

1445
01:14:03,886 --> 01:14:07,822
Frankly, I don't share
any of your sense of
pessimism or alarm.

1446
01:14:09,625 --> 01:14:12,685
And this ridiculous
self-flagellation,

1447
01:14:12,762 --> 01:14:15,230
in my view,
is just depressing.

1448
01:14:16,332 --> 01:14:17,424
No!

1449
01:14:19,301 --> 01:14:23,738
And threatening to derail
the whole enterprise.

1450
01:14:25,407 --> 01:14:30,538
Look. If there is
anyone here who thinks
we're gonna fail,

1451
01:14:31,514 --> 01:14:33,539
they better leave now,

1452
01:14:34,617 --> 01:14:36,847
or it'll infect
everyone else.

1453
01:14:43,893 --> 01:14:45,224
No one?

1454
01:14:48,664 --> 01:14:50,063
Right.

1455
01:14:51,433 --> 01:14:52,559
Good.

1456
01:14:55,037 --> 01:14:58,837
Now, I suggest instead of
festering around the hotel
for the next five days,

1457
01:14:58,908 --> 01:15:01,877
we all go
our separate ways
over Easter.

1458
01:15:03,579 --> 01:15:06,070
But before we go,
Caroline and I
would like you

1459
01:15:06,148 --> 01:15:08,548
to join us for a little
celebratory dinner

1460
01:15:08,617 --> 01:15:11,677
at Patrick Terrail's
new place.

1461
01:15:11,754 --> 01:15:14,518
Celebrate?
Celebrate what, David?

1462
01:15:14,590 --> 01:15:16,353
The fact that we're
all gonna be working
at Burger King?

1463
01:15:16,425 --> 01:15:19,622
What are we celebrating?
It's my birthday, Bob!

1464
01:15:24,300 --> 01:15:29,670
I'd like to
celebrate my birthday
with a few friends.

1465
01:15:36,178 --> 01:15:38,112
(PIANO PLAYING UPBEAT TUNE)

1466
01:15:41,584 --> 01:15:42,846
Look, is that
Neil Diamond?

1467
01:15:42,918 --> 01:15:44,818
<i>(SINGING) Frost and Nixon,</i>
<i>Frost and Nixon</i>

1468
01:15:44,887 --> 01:15:46,218
And is that Sammy Cahn?

1469
01:15:46,288 --> 01:15:47,414
<i>Go together like</i>
<i>Prancer and Vixen</i>

1470
01:15:47,489 --> 01:15:48,854
David,
did you hear that?

1471
01:15:48,924 --> 01:15:50,653
<i>Soaring through the airwaves</i>

1472
01:15:50,726 --> 01:15:53,024
Jesus, that's Hugh Hefner.

1473
01:15:53,095 --> 01:15:54,119
Oh, my God.

1474
01:15:54,196 --> 01:15:55,424
<i>Hoping for several</i>
<i>hefty paydays</i>

1475
01:15:55,497 --> 01:15:56,930
Yeah, I think it is.
With Michael York.

1476
01:15:56,999 --> 01:15:58,296
That's gotta be Bunnies.

1477
01:15:58,367 --> 01:15:59,994
Those are Bunnies?
Those are real Bunnies?

1478
01:16:00,069 --> 01:16:01,468
<i>Frost and Nixon,</i>
<i>Frost and Nixon</i>

1479
01:16:01,537 --> 01:16:02,663
<i>Go together</i>
<i>like Mason and Dixon</i>

1480
01:16:02,738 --> 01:16:06,230
David, just putting it
all together it's the most
extraordinary accomplishment.

1481
01:16:06,308 --> 01:16:07,866
<i>Frost lines up with Dicky...</i>

1482
01:16:07,943 --> 01:16:09,171
No one else
could have done that.

1483
01:16:09,245 --> 01:16:11,975
And these interviews
are always gonna be around
for future generations

1484
01:16:12,047 --> 01:16:14,345
of academics and
political historians.

1485
01:16:14,416 --> 01:16:15,405
That bad?

1486
01:16:15,484 --> 01:16:17,213
<i>He saved it</i>

1487
01:16:17,286 --> 01:16:20,414
<i>He wrote a book</i>
<i>Now here's the hook</i>

1488
01:16:20,489 --> 01:16:22,013
David!

1489
01:16:22,091 --> 01:16:23,115
Patrick.

1490
01:16:23,192 --> 01:16:26,161
<i>He's not a crook</i>
<i>He's paid by David</i>

1491
01:16:26,695 --> 01:16:28,253
(GUESTS APPLAUDING)

1492
01:16:30,799 --> 01:16:32,926
(PLAYING CLASSICAL MUSIC)

1493
01:17:08,404 --> 01:17:12,864
My, what
a festive atmosphere.
Please, don't get up.

1494
01:17:12,942 --> 01:17:16,537
I take it from this
that the interviews
have gone well?

1495
01:17:16,612 --> 01:17:18,273
Better than that, ma'am.
It's a shutout.

1496
01:17:18,347 --> 01:17:20,542
The President's sitting
on an 1 1-0 lead.

1497
01:17:20,616 --> 01:17:22,641
Really? Well.
Yeah.

1498
01:17:22,718 --> 01:17:24,948
Well, that is
most gratifying.

1499
01:17:29,258 --> 01:17:32,455
I'm so glad it's all
gone according to plan.

1500
01:17:47,710 --> 01:17:49,007
(SIGHS) I see.

1501
01:17:50,679 --> 01:17:52,704
Is there nothing
we can do?

1502
01:17:54,350 --> 01:17:55,510
Really?

1503
01:17:57,720 --> 01:18:00,848
(SIGHING) Right. Well, thanks
for letting me know.

1504
01:18:07,930 --> 01:18:10,899
It's true.
They've dropped
the Australian show.

1505
01:18:10,966 --> 01:18:13,298
Oh, no, David.

1506
01:18:13,369 --> 01:18:17,135
They felt that I needed
to reevaluate my priorities.

1507
01:18:19,508 --> 01:18:22,568
Now my producer's worried
that the London show
will follow.

1508
01:18:25,848 --> 01:18:27,179
I'm in this
for everything I've got,

1509
01:18:27,249 --> 01:18:30,946
and there's still
no guarantee it'll ever
see the light of day.

1510
01:18:33,055 --> 01:18:37,583
What have I done?
What was I thinking?
Why didn't anyone stop me?

1511
01:18:37,659 --> 01:18:39,320
They should have
physically stopped me!

1512
01:18:39,395 --> 01:18:40,987
No, no, no. Shh.

1513
01:18:48,504 --> 01:18:52,406
Look, we don't have
to go out tonight.
Why don't we stay in?

1514
01:18:54,476 --> 01:18:55,568
Hmm?

1515
01:18:59,882 --> 01:19:03,283
I'll go down to Trader Vic's
and bring something back.

1516
01:19:04,987 --> 01:19:06,579
Steak or fish?

1517
01:19:08,090 --> 01:19:09,421
David?

1518
01:19:13,662 --> 01:19:16,256
Don't worry. I'll call
from the restaurant.

1519
01:19:21,437 --> 01:19:22,426
(DOOR CLOSES)

1520
01:19:47,930 --> 01:19:50,831
(TELEPHONE RINGING)

1521
01:20:01,343 --> 01:20:05,370
I'll have a cheeseburger.

1522
01:20:05,814 --> 01:20:10,046
<i>NIXON: Mmm. That sounds good.</i>
<i>I used to love cheeseburgers,</i>

1523
01:20:11,120 --> 01:20:13,281
<i>but Dr. Lundgren</i>
<i>made me give them up.</i>

1524
01:20:13,355 --> 01:20:16,882
<i>He switched me</i>
<i>to cottage cheese</i>
<i>and pineapple instead.</i>

1525
01:20:17,960 --> 01:20:20,292
He calls them
my Hawaiian burgers,

1526
01:20:20,863 --> 01:20:22,763
but they don't taste
like burgers at all.

1527
01:20:22,831 --> 01:20:24,992
<i>They taste like Styrofoam.</i>

1528
01:20:28,770 --> 01:20:30,670
I hope I'm not disturbing.

1529
01:20:31,507 --> 01:20:32,906
No.

1530
01:20:32,975 --> 01:20:34,602
<i>It's a Friday night.</i>

1531
01:20:34,676 --> 01:20:39,204
You've probably
got somebody there
whom you're entertaining.

1532
01:20:40,649 --> 01:20:41,877
No.

1533
01:20:42,017 --> 01:20:43,712
Well, then
what are you doing?

1534
01:20:44,453 --> 01:20:46,421
<i>A handsome</i>
<i>young fellow,</i>

1535
01:20:46,955 --> 01:20:52,018
an eligible young bachelor
alone on a Friday night.

1536
01:20:53,695 --> 01:20:59,156
If you must know,
I'm preparing
for our final session.

1537
01:21:00,035 --> 01:21:02,196
The all-important
final session.

1538
01:21:02,271 --> 01:21:04,398
<i>Yes.</i>
Watergate.

1539
01:21:05,440 --> 01:21:08,637
<i>'Cause I guess</i>
<i>the way you handle</i>
<i>Watergate's gonna determine</i>

1540
01:21:08,710 --> 01:21:12,009
whether these interviews
are a success or a failure.

1541
01:21:14,283 --> 01:21:16,114
Should I be nervous?

1542
01:21:17,920 --> 01:21:22,016
Well, I'm gonna
give it my best shot.

1543
01:21:22,391 --> 01:21:27,385
Quite right.
No holds barred.
No holds barred.

1544
01:21:28,263 --> 01:21:30,163
You know, it's strange.

1545
01:21:31,033 --> 01:21:34,491
Now, we have sat in chairs
opposite one another,

1546
01:21:34,603 --> 01:21:37,868
talking for hours,
it seems, days on end,

1547
01:21:37,940 --> 01:21:41,137
and yet I've hardly
gotten to know you.

1548
01:21:42,211 --> 01:21:45,271
One of my people,
as part of the preparation

1549
01:21:45,347 --> 01:21:48,009
for this interview,
she did a profile on you.

1550
01:21:48,584 --> 01:21:52,611
And I'm sorry to say
that I just got around
to reading it tonight.

1551
01:21:55,557 --> 01:21:58,355
There's some
interesting stuff
in there.

1552
01:21:58,427 --> 01:22:01,521
Your Methodist background,
the modest circumstances,

1553
01:22:01,597 --> 01:22:07,934
and then you're off
to a grand university
full of richer, posher types.

1554
01:22:08,003 --> 01:22:10,494
What was it? Oxford?

1555
01:22:11,840 --> 01:22:13,330
Cambridge.

1556
01:22:14,309 --> 01:22:18,473
Did the snobs there
look down on you, too?

1557
01:22:18,747 --> 01:22:19,771
(CHUCKLES)

1558
01:22:19,848 --> 01:22:24,410
Of course they did.
That's our tragedy,
isn't it, Mr. Frost?

1559
01:22:25,254 --> 01:22:30,487
No matter how high we get,
they still look down at us.

1560
01:22:31,593 --> 01:22:33,561
I really don't know
what you're talking about.

1561
01:22:33,629 --> 01:22:35,290
Yes, you do.

1562
01:22:35,831 --> 01:22:39,733
Now, come on.
No matter how many awards

1563
01:22:39,801 --> 01:22:43,032
or column inches
are written about you

1564
01:22:43,105 --> 01:22:47,667
<i>or how high</i>
<i>the elected office is for me,</i>
<i>it's still not enough.</i>

1565
01:22:48,543 --> 01:22:50,807
We still feel
like the little man,

1566
01:22:50,879 --> 01:22:55,646
the loser they told us
we were a hundred times.

1567
01:22:56,318 --> 01:23:01,017
The smart-asses at college,
the high-ups, the well-born,

1568
01:23:01,890 --> 01:23:06,350
the people whose
respect we really wanted,
really craved.

1569
01:23:06,762 --> 01:23:12,928
And isn't that
why we work so hard now,
why we fight for every inch,

1570
01:23:13,001 --> 01:23:16,664
<i>scrambling our way up</i>
<i>in undignified fashion?</i>

1571
01:23:16,738 --> 01:23:21,835
If we're honest for a minute,
if we reflect privately
just for a moment,

1572
01:23:21,910 --> 01:23:28,782
if we allow ourselves
a glimpse into that shadowy
place we call our soul,

1573
01:23:29,051 --> 01:23:33,818
isn't that why
we're here now?
The two of us?

1574
01:23:34,056 --> 01:23:37,651
Looking for a way
back into the sun,

1575
01:23:38,160 --> 01:23:42,494
<i>into the limelight,</i>
<i>back onto the winner's podium.</i>

1576
01:23:42,564 --> 01:23:46,125
Because we could feel
it slipping away.

1577
01:23:46,201 --> 01:23:49,170
We were headed,
both of us, for the dirt!

1578
01:23:49,237 --> 01:23:53,697
A place the snobs
always told us
that we'd end up.

1579
01:23:53,775 --> 01:23:54,901
Face in the dust.

1580
01:23:54,976 --> 01:23:59,106
Humiliated all the more
for having tried
so pitifully hard.

1581
01:23:59,181 --> 01:24:01,581
Well, to hell with that!

1582
01:24:01,650 --> 01:24:03,880
We're not gonna
let that happen,
either of us.

1583
01:24:03,952 --> 01:24:05,647
We're gonna
show those bums.

1584
01:24:05,721 --> 01:24:09,248
We're gonna make them choke
on our continued success,

1585
01:24:09,324 --> 01:24:14,990
our continued headlines,
our continued awards
and power and glory!

1586
01:24:15,063 --> 01:24:19,090
We are gonna make
those motherfuckers choke!

1587
01:24:30,345 --> 01:24:31,710
Am I right?

1588
01:24:33,081 --> 01:24:36,881
You are.
Except only one of us can win.

1589
01:24:38,053 --> 01:24:39,042
Yes.

1590
01:24:41,923 --> 01:24:47,259
And I shall be
your fiercest adversary.

1591
01:24:47,829 --> 01:24:51,925
I shall come at you
with everything I got,

1592
01:24:52,868 --> 01:24:59,467
because the limelight
can only shine on one of us.

1593
01:25:01,042 --> 01:25:05,376
And for the other,
it'll be the wilderness,

1594
01:25:07,249 --> 01:25:12,448
with nothing and no one
for company

1595
01:25:14,156 --> 01:25:17,717
but those voices
ringing in our head.

1596
01:25:32,507 --> 01:25:37,467
You can probably tell
I've had a drink.

1597
